## Boundary Rules (where new docs go)

The structure follows one mechanical rule: **top-level files are universal
singletons (one per app); plural folders hold variable-count items
(zero, one, or many per app)**.

- **`api-clients/`** — one file per backend service consumed. Naming:
  lowercase, short (`publisher.md`, `backoffice.md`). Documents the
  endpoints used, request/response shapes, error handling specific to
  that service, and known divergences in how the service's contract is
  used. Cross-cutting client concerns (interceptors, token refresh,
  factory pattern) belong in `architecture.md` and `error-handling.md`.

- **`features/`** — one file per UI feature module (typically aligns
  with a top-level directory under `src/features/`). Naming: lowercase,
  short. Documents the routes, key components, hooks, state, and i18n
  keys for that feature. Create a new file when a new feature module
  is added; extend an existing file when adding a view inside an
  existing feature.

- **`business-context.md`** — exactly one per app. Product framing only;
  no code maps, no design tokens, no per-feature details.

- **Every api-client doc** ends with a `## Known Divergences (Do Not
  Replicate)` section listing real footguns in how this service is
  currently consumed.

